                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A work on Sufi spiritual life by Husain ibn ‘Alim ibn Ḥasan
                            al-Ḥusainī <locus from="140v" to="140v">f. 140v</locus>, known as Amir
                            Ḥusainī or Fakhr al-Sādāt (d. A.H. 718, A.D. 1318). It is in mixed prose
                            and poetry, interspersed with stories and sayings of the holy men. It
                            commences with an amplificatory preface in which he praises the prophet
                            Muhammad and the first four Caliphs. The main text is a guidance for the
                            spiritual traveller in various stages in his path to purity, divided
                            into twenty-eight chapters (faṣl). According to the author in faṣl 28,
                            Nuzhat al-arvāḥ was completed in A.H 711, when he was 40 years old: در
                            ختم کتاب ای شب گرد بدروز سال عمرت بچهل رسیده و تو از جهل خود نارسیده...
                            در شهور سنه احدی عشر و سبعماته مشاطه نشاط فکر بر بساط گردن و گوش هر یک
                            را بزیور فصاحت و بلاغت مقرط و موشح گردانید It has been a popular Sufi
                            work, widely copied and received several commentaries. </summary>
